{
  "text": "We observed that exenatide, when administered intravenously in both healthy subjects and patients with type 2 diabetes, 1) markedly suppressed duodenal motility and flow, 2) slowed small intestinal transit, 3) decreased 3-OMG absorption, and 4) delayed and suppressed glycemic increments in response to an intraduodenal glucose infusion. The dose of exenatide (7.5 mg) was within the usual clinical range and was infused in a regimen shown previously to achieve steady therapeutic plasma concentrations [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
